body:
This little code example triggers a "Parameter values cannot be hierarchical" error with verilator version `Verilator 5.041 devel rev v5.040-182-g40ca0527d`:

```verilog
interface Foo #(parameter WIDTH_BITS = 128);
endinterface

module Bar (Foo foo_in);
    localparam WIDTH_BITS = foo_in.WIDTH_BITS;
endmodule

module top;
    Foo #(.WIDTH_BITS(12)) foo ();
    Bar bar(.foo_in(foo));
    initial begin
        $display("bar.WIDTH_BITS: %0d", bar.WIDTH_BITS);
    end
endmodule
```

This is incorrect because interface ports do not define a scope and therefore `foo_in.WIDTH_BITS` is not a hierarchical name, but a member select.  For reference please see section 23.7 "Member selects and hierarchical names" of the SV spec. See also commentary from the legendary dave_59[1] [here](https://verificationacademy.com/forums/t/access-parameterized-interface-ports-size-from-within-module/30796) and [here](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29979408/in-systemverilog-is-it-allowed-to-read-a-parameter-from-an-interface#comment48108146_29989539).

Interestingly, an older version of verilator, `Verilator 5.036 2025-04-27 rev v5.036` does not flag the above code as an error. I did a little digging and this is the commit that introduced this error: 7f85d7f45386993e942dd201bb8ec4cf382ffa29

1.  Dave Rich, who worked for Gateway that invented verilog, and then Co-Design Automation which invented SystemVerilog and has been on the standards committee all along

